<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-562-953  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 562 953.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>ACM Transactions on Database Systems  Sept 1990 v15 n3 p359(26).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Data caching issues in an information retrieval system.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alonso, Rafael; Barbara, Daniel; Garcia-Molina, Hector.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many of the current information retrieval systems store all thedata at a central node, but this is slowly changing as the numberof microcomputers and users grows.andP;  There is a need to exploreways to make update propagation less costly while retaining theadvantages of caching.andP;  Two ideas are to permit the user toexplicitly define the information of interest and to cache onlythat information, and to permit a weaker type of consistencybetween the central data and its copies, which makes itunnecessary to update the cached copy every time a change occursin the central data.andP;  A cached value that deviates from thecentral value in a controlled way is called a quasi-copy; managingquasi-copies is called quasi-caching.andP;  Quasi-copies significantlyreduce the overhead incurred in managing replicated data, and thedata is available even if communication lines or the central siteare down.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Cache MemoryInformation Storage and RetrievalData BasesReplicated Data BasesShared FilesDistributed Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Model parameters. (table)Basic model. (chart)Extended network model. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>